import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, accuracy_score, f1_score

# read dataset
data = pd.read_csv("fish_nb.csv", header=None)

# convert horizontal dataset to vertical format
data = data.set_index(0).T
data.columns = ["Species","Weight","Height","Width","Length1","Length2","Length3"]

# convert numeric columns
for col in ["Weight","Height","Width","Length1","Length2","Length3"]:
    data[col] = data[col].astype(float)

# encode species
le = LabelEncoder()
data["Species"] = le.fit_transform(data["Species"])

X = data[["Weight","Height","Width","Length1","Length2","Length3"]]
y = data["Species"]

# Naive Bayes model
model = GaussianNB()
model.fit(X,y)

y_pred = model.predict(X)

print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y,y_pred))
print("Precision:", precision_score(y,y_pred,average="macro"))
print("Recall:", recall_score(y,y_pred,average="macro"))
print("F1 Score:", f1_score(y,y_pred,average="macro"))

Problem Understanding & Aim
To classify fish species using features like weight, height, width and lengths using Naïve Bayes classifier.

Data Collection & Pre-Processing
Dataset contains fish measurements and species. Species labels are converted into numerical values.

Model Design / Algorithm Selection
Naïve Bayes classifier is selected for classification.

Implementation – Model Building
Import libraries. Load dataset. Train Naïve Bayes model. Predict species.

Evaluation & Output
Model performance evaluated using Accuracy, Precision, Recall and F1 Score.

Viva / Concept Clarity
Naïve Bayes is a probabilistic classifier based on Bayes theorem with the assumption of feature independence.
